I"¡<p>Instead of using the flakey ESXi HTML5 console viewer to attach to a VMâ€™s display, itâ€™s possible to use VNC for that.
Since this is not officially supported by VMWare, the steps to activate VNC are only possible on the command line.</p>

<ol>
  <li>To open VNC ports in the ESXi firewall, edit <code class="highlighter-rouge">/etc/vmware/firewall/vncServer.xml</code>:
    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;ConfigRoot&gt;
  &lt;service&gt;
    &lt;id&gt;vncServer&lt;/id&gt;
    &lt;rule id='0000'&gt;
      &lt;direction&gt;inbound&lt;/direction&gt;
      &lt;protocol&gt;tcp&lt;/protocol&gt;
      &lt;porttype&gt;dst&lt;/porttype&gt;
      &lt;port&gt;
        &lt;begin&gt;5900&lt;/begin&gt;
        &lt;end&gt;5999&lt;/end&gt;
      &lt;/port&gt;
    &lt;/rule&gt;
    &lt;enabled&gt;true&lt;/enabled&gt;
    &lt;required&gt;false&lt;/required&gt;
  &lt;/service&gt;
&lt;/ConfigRoot&gt;
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>Refresh firewall rules:
    <div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>esxcli network firewall refresh
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>Power-off VM.</li>
  <li>Add those lines to the VMâ€™s <em>.vmx</em> configuration file:
    <div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>RemoteDisplay.vnc.enabled = "TRUE"
RemoteDisplay.vnc.port = "5901"
RemoteDisplay.vnc.password = "&lt;$PASSWORD&gt;"
RemoteDisplay.vnc.keyMap = "de"
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>Power-on VM.</li>
  <li>Connect to VM display with a VNC client via <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;$ESX_HOST&gt;:5901</code>.</li>
</ol>

